Chinese President Xi Jinping (fifth from left) and other participants pose for a "family photo" during the 2018 APEC Economic Leaders' Meeting in Port Moresby, Papua New Guinea on Sunday. Photo: XinhuaThe annual APEC summit of Asia-Pacific leaders will go virtual in 2021 to avoid travel risks associated with the global coronavirus pandemic, 2021 hosts New Zealand said Tuesday.New Zealand's Foreign Minister Winston Peters said in a statement that holding the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation summit online, instead of in Auckland, was a "pragmatic" response to the crisis.More than 20,000 people were expected to visit New Zealand for the 21-member summit in November 2021 and numerous lead-in meetings.The decision to go virtual also eases a logistical headache for organizers, who were struggling to find sufficient hotel rooms in Auckland after construction of the planned venue was delayed by a huge fire in October 2019.AFP 
